polo team? What does that mean
for volleyball?

32:42.360 --> 32:47.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a dangerous line here
where the very
natural thing to do would be to
have three

32:47.365 --> 32:49.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
revenue-generating sports and
get rid of all
the others.

32:49.801 --> 32:53.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, Professor
Yankah has an alternative
for athletes who aren't
students.

32:53.805 --> 32:57.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EKOW YANKAH: If there are young
people who
are not at all interested in
being student

32:57.776 --> 33:03.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
athletes, and their life's
project is to develop
their particular athletic
talent, there ought

33:03.748 --> 33:07.485 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be professional developmental
leagues into
which they can go.

33:07.519 --> 33:11.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Right now, of
course, the main
option for young basketball
players remains

33:11.523 --> 33:13.525 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
going to an NCAA college.

33:13.558 --> 33:17.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do almost all of them think they
are going
pro, that is, people who play in
Division

33:18.029 --> 33:18.830 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I college, let's say?

33:18.864 --> 33:20.065 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ED O'BANNON: In my experience,
yes.

33:20.098 --> 33:22.067 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And it's a delusion
right?

33:22.100 --> 33:28.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ED O'BANNON: It's a delusion,
but I think
it's the right delusion. You
have to think

33:28.807 --> 33:31.676 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you're going to go in order to
get there.

33:31.710 --> 33:39.317 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: OK, so what
happened to O'Bannon's
Liberty Patriots? Hoop dreams
dashed, theirs

33:39.351 --> 33:42.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and by this time ours, they
wound up losing
67-61.

33:42.787 --> 33:48.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ED O'BANNON: As the coaching
staff, we tip
our hats to you guys, because
you played hard

33:48.994 --> 33:50.929 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
all season.

33:50.962 --> 33:55.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: What you guys did today and
these previous
four years, you will get to
further your education,

33:55.967 --> 33:58.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and get it paid for. That's the
goal.

33:58.336 --> 34:03.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And maybe even
getting paid extra
in cash.

34:03.041 --> 34:09.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, in the end, what's
happened to the
lawsuits? Well, EA Sports
actually settled

34:09.281 --> 34:14.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for roughly $60 million, with
thousands of
players, past and present,
getting, on average,

34:14.953 --> 34:20.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about $1,600 each, the money
finally awarded
just this week.

34:20.592 --> 34:28.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 2014, the court ruled the
NCAA's refusal
to pay players was an antitrust
violation,

34:28.900 --> 34:35.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and also ordered up to $5,000
per student
athlete be put in trust for
using their likenesses.

34:35.674 --> 34:41.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the NCAA appealed, and the
money award
was reversed.

34:41.413 --> 34:49.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, this Tuesday, O'Bannon's
lawyers asked
the Supreme Court to review the
case.

34:49.187 --> 35:01.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Henderson, Nevada, this is
economics correspondent
Paul Solman for the "PBS
NewsHour."

35:01.566 --> 35:14.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The popular theme
park SeaWorld
has been under ever-growing
criticism for

35:14.679 --> 35:18.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the way it breeds and shows its
popular orca
whales.

35:18.917 --> 35:22.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now SeaWorld is bowing to
pressure and making
a big change.

35:22.620 --> 35:24.789 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has the story.

35:24.823 --> 35:33.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Orca whales have
been entertaining
audiences at SeaWorld parks
since 1964. Once

35:33.498 --> 35:37.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
feared -- they're commonly known
as killer
whales -- they have become
hugely popular

35:37.836 --> 35:39.537 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and even beloved.

35:39.571 --> 35:45.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today's announcement, made with
the Humane
Society, means the era of public
exhibition

35:45.243 --> 35:47.379 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is, gradually at least, coming
to an end.

35:47.412 --> 35:51.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOEL MANBY, CEO and President,
SeaWorld: Current
orcas under our care will be the
last generation

35:51.349 --> 35:54.486 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at SeaWorld. We're going to
phase out our
theatrical shows.

35:54.519 --> 35:59.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: SeaWorld is
ending its breeding
program for the animals, though
it's keeping

35:59.357 --> 36:01.259 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the whales it already has.

36:01.292 --> 36:07.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the Orlando-based company
says the shows
will give way to what it calls
inspiring natural

36:07.298 --> 36:13.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
orca encounters. Animal rights
activists have
long criticized keeping the
animals in captivity.

36:13.605 --> 36:18.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: Any of us would be
miserable if we
had to spend out life living in
a bathtub.

36:18.943 --> 36:23.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And orcas at SeaWorld are just
as miserable.
They spend their lives confined
to tiny tanks,

36:23.314 --> 36:26.284 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
where they go mad from
confinement and boredom.

36:26.317 --> 36:32.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The parks came
under new scrutiny
in 2010 after one of the whales
drowned a

36:32.090 --> 36:38.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
trainer. That attack later
became the peg
for 2013's "Blackfish," a
documentary examining

36:38.997 --> 36:42.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the effects of captivity on
killer whales.

36:42.067 --> 36:48.673 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The company also faced
regulatory and legislative
efforts to ban orca captivity.
And ticket

36:48.706 --> 36:53.044 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sales to the parks have dropped
significantly.

36:53.078 --> 36:57.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we're joined now by the man
who made today's
announcement, SeaWorld CEO and
president Joel

36:57.382 --> 37:04.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Manby, and by Wayne Pacelle, CEO
of the Humane
Society of the United States, a
longtime critic

37:04.055 --> 37:07.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of SeaWorld that worked with it
on the new
reform measures.

37:08.026 --> 37:08.827 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to both of you.

37:08.860 --> 37:10.628 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Joel Manby, let me start with
you.

37:10.662 --> 37:14.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is this an acknowledgment that
raising and
using the whales for public
exhibition has

37:14.899 --> 37:16.801 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
been wrong?

37:16.835 --> 37:19.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOEL MANBY, CEO and President,
SeaWorld: Jeffrey,
what's really clear to me -- I
have been CEO

37:19.971 --> 37:23.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for about 11 months now -- is
that society
has shifted.

37:23.608 --> 37:30.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And people's view of having
these majestic,
very large animals under human
care has changed

37:30.415 --> 37:34.519 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
over time. And more and more
people are becoming
uncomfortable with it.

37:34.552 --> 37:38.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I had to make some difficult
decisions
to move the company forward, and
I felt that

37:38.957 --> 37:44.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the right thing to do for the
company and
all things considered is to end
our breeding

37:44.262 --> 37:46.064 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
program.

37:46.097 --> 37:49.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The right thing
to do for the
company, so should it be seen
mostly as a

37:49.033 --> 37:50.835 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
business decision?

37:50.869 --> 37:56.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOEL MANBY: You know what? I
think any business
in today's world has to be
connected to a

37:56.508 --> 37:58.276 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
core set of values.

37:58.309 --> 38:02.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And our core set of values is to
help animals
in the wild. And a lot of people
don't maybe

38:02.914 --> 38:06.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
realize that about SeaWorld, but
we have the
best zoological organization, I
think, in

38:06.784 --> 38:11.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the world. We're passionate
about animals.
We're passionate about animals
in the wild.

38:11.055 --> 38:17.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I felt that the orca issue
was an overhang
for us that was stopping our
incredible story

38:17.729 --> 38:23.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from being told to a country
that's changing.
And I think it's great that the
millennials,

38:23.201 --> 38:28.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the younger folks care about
conservation,
they care about animals. We do,
too, and I

38:28.606 --> 38:30.375 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
wanted them to hear our story
more and more.

38:30.408 --> 38:34.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, so Wayne
Pacelle, as
I said, a longtime critic of
SeaWorld, now

38:34.712 --> 38:38.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
working with them, what do you
see as the
importance of this move, and
what would a

38:38.416 --> 38:44.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
move towards a more educational
or more natural
approach be? What do you want to
see happen

38:44.556 --> 38:46.457 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now?

38:46.491 --> 38:48.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WAYNE PACELLE, President and
CEO, Humane Society
of the United States: Well, we
celebrate the

38:48.326 --> 38:53.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
end of breeding of orcas in
activity. This
has been a long-held aspiration
for the Humane

38:53.231 --> 38:56.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Society of the U.S. and so many
other groups
in our field.

38:56.801 --> 39:02.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obviously, the atmospherics on
this issue
changed dramatically after the
airing of "Blackfish."

39:02.207 --> 39:07.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In terms of these animals, they
are obviously
long-lived animals. They are
going to be around

39:07.712 --> 39:11.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if they are not released into
the wild. And
there are obviously a whole set
of challenges

39:11.916 --> 39:14.319 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
if that were to be contemplated.

39:14.352 --> 39:20.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We obviously are very focused on
the idea
of an orca-centric experience,
that the trainers

39:20.592 --> 39:25.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are allowing them to exhibit
their natural
behaviors, that they're
exercised, that within

39:25.797 --> 39:28.099 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the captive setting, there's
enrichment.

39:28.132 --> 39:33.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a great challenge, with
these highly
intelligent, complex, sociable
animals who

39:33.404 --> 39:38.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
live in pods in the wild. We
think there's
a ceiling in terms of how much
can be done

39:38.543 --> 39:43.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for them, but obviously SeaWorld
and its staff
need to do their best to
accommodate their

39:43.781 --> 39:45.583 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
needs.

39:45.617 --> 39:47.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What about, Mr.
Pacelle, staying
with you, going -- I wonder if
you would go

39:47.585 --> 39:52.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
further, because your
organization has also
been critical of keeping
dolphins in captivity.

39:52.557 --> 39:57.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are you pushing SeaWorld to go
there? Do you
expect this to continue to
something like

39:57.729 --> 39:59.564 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that any time soon?

39:59.597 --> 40:04.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WAYNE PACELLE: Well, we think
there's actually
a very artful solution, which
is, if SeaWorld

40:04.435 --> 40:11.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has continuing needs for animals
to populate
its expeditions, if they can get
animals who

40:11.709 --> 40:16.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are beached or otherwise in
distress from
the wild and those animals can
be brought

40:16.080 --> 40:21.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in, rehabilitated and in some
cases, if they
cannot be re-released, then they
can meet

40:21.286 --> 40:23.087 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
those needs.

40:23.121 --> 40:26.791 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And that is a de facto
sanctuary. That's what
big cat sanctuaries and chimp
sanctuaries

40:26.824 --> 40:32.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and lots of other animal-based
sanctuaries
do. Some animals simply can't be
released

40:32.397 --> 40:39.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into the wild again. And a lot
of very progressive
zoos and others are relying on
rescues to

40:39.070 --> 40:40.405 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
populate their exhibits.

40:40.438 --> 40:43.174 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we hope that's the direction
of SeaWorld
in the years ahead.

40:43.207 --> 40:44.609 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, what about
that, Mr.
Manby, because...

40:44.642 --> 40:46.411 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOEL MANBY: If I could....

40:46.444 --> 40:49.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes, go ahead. I
want to get
your response on where you see
this going,

40:49.314 --> 40:53.685 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and why not, if there's cultural
shifts, move
to other animals like dolphins?

40:53.718 --> 40:58.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOEL MANBY: Well, a point that
Wayne made
that is very important -- a lot
of people

40:58.523 --> 41:05.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
don't realize it -- is that
there is a tremendous
need for rescue operations, and
the capacity

41:05.096 --> 41:07.532 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is much lower than the demand.

41:07.565 --> 41:12.370 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And one of the things I
announced today was,
SeaWorld is committing $50
million over the

41:12.403 --> 41:17.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
next five years, with a goal of
being the
largest rescue organization in
the world.

41:17.842 --> 41:24.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And just in the last year, we
rescue seven
animals a day, 1,000 dolphins
stranded last

41:24.782 --> 41:29.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
year alone. There's hundreds and
hundreds
of sea lions in California that
we save.

41:29.787 --> 41:33.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This good work can't continue
unless SeaWorld
has the expertise and the
facilities.

41:34.025 --> 41:38.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Is there, Mr.
Manby -- with
the orcas, you have said you --
it would be

41:38.796 --> 41:40.898 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dangerous to release the ones
you have.

41:40.932 --> 41:46.838 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
What about, though, on a
case-by-case basis
or moving them, transferring
them to some

41:46.871 --> 41:48.506 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
kind of transitional area?

41:48.539 --> 41:50.241 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
JOEL MANBY: Yes.

41:50.274 --> 41:54.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, this is something that
actually
Wayne and I have talked a lot
about. We don't

41:54.145 --> 41:58.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
always agree on everything, and
we won't,
but we're trying to look for
common ground.

41:58.316 --> 42:05.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the truth is, any research
you read, any
peer-reviewed research, a whale
that's born

42:05.390 --> 42:08.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into human care is not a good
candidate for
release.

42:09.026 --> 42:14.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, in the history of
mankind, no whale
or dolphin born under human care
has been

42:15.032 --> 42:19.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
released successfully. The only
time it has
been done successfully, if
they're wild, they're

42:19.470 --> 42:21.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
brought in for a short period of
time and
released.

42:21.439 --> 42:25.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have four whales that were
taken from the
wild over 35 years ago. They're
quite old

42:25.943 --> 42:30.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
now. They have been under human
care for a
long, long time. We don't think
it's worth

42:30.581 --> 42:32.417 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the risk for those four whales.

42:32.450 --> 42:36.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Mr. Pacelle, just
in our last
minute, I want to ask you about
the largest

42:36.487 --> 42:42.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
context here. Do you see this as
part of a
movement, in the way that zoos
and aquariums

42:42.960 --> 42:48.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and all look at the treatment of
animals,
movies, and so a much larger
cultural shift

42:48.666 --> 42:49.367 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
here?

42:49.400 --> 42:51.369 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WAYNE PACELLE: No question.

42:51.402 --> 42:55.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have got a book coming out
next month called
"The Humane Economy," and my
argument is that

42:55.940 --> 43:02.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
business and commerce must marry
itself with
these emergent values about
animals and their

43:02.313 --> 43:04.215 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
well-being.

43:04.248 --> 43:08.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was March last year we saw
Ringling Brothers
give up its traveling elephant
acts. We have

43:08.453 --> 43:12.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
seen movies migrate away from
live animals
to computer-generated imagery.
We're seeing

43:12.657 --> 43:17.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
changes in the food sector,
where companies
like Wal-Mart or Kroger or
McDonald's are

43:17.795 --> 43:21.132 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now buying their products that
come from more
humane farms.

43:21.165 --> 43:28.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a cultural-wide shift.
And this happens
to be one manifestation, with a
live entertainment

43:28.039 --> 43:31.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
